{{Taxobox | name = Aceramarca Gracile Opossum<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Gardner | pages = 6}}</ref> | status = LC | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=iucn>Patterson, B. & Solari S. 2008. [http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/9416/0 ''Gracilinanus aceramarcae''.] The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2014.3. Downloaded on 30 March 2015.</ref> | regnum = [[Animalia]] | phylum = [[Chordata]] | classis = [[Mammalia]] | ordo = [[Didelphimorphia]] | familia = [[Didelphidae]] | genus = ''[[Gracilinanus]]'' | species = '''''G. aceramarcae''''' | binomial = ''Gracilinanus aceramarcae'' | binomial_authority = ([[George Henry Hamilton Tate|Tate]], 1931) | synonyms = | range_map = Aceramarca Gracile Mouse Opossum area.png | range_map_caption = Aceramarca Gracile Opossum range }}
The '''Aceramarca gracile opossum''' or '''Bolivian gracile opossum''' (''Gracilinanus aceramarcae'') is a species of [[opossum]]. It is native to [[Bolivia]] and [[Peru]], where it occurs in tropical [[elfin forest]] habitat.<ref name=iucn/>
This opossum is mostly arboreal, but it may forage on the ground for food.<ref name=iucn/>
This species has been recorded at only six locations, but it is not considered to be threatened because its habitat is relatively secure from [[deforestation]] and other threats at this time.<ref name=iucn/>
This mouse opossum does not have a pouch. It is reddish or grayish brown in color with a cream-colored belly and a dark eye ring. It is up to {{convert|13.5|cm|in|frac=3}} long, not including its slender, scaly tail, which may be over {{convert|15|cm|in|0}} long.<ref>[http://www.edgeofexistence.org/mammals/species_info.php?id=35 Aceramarca Gracile Mouse Opossum.] Evolutionarily Distinct and Globally Endangered (EDGE).</ref>
