'''Elwyn LaVerne Simons''' (July 14, 1930 – March 6, 2016) was an American [[paleontologist]], [[paleozoology|paleozoologist]], and a [[wildlife conservation]]ist for [[primate]]s.<ref name=obit>[https://today.duke.edu/2016/03/simonselwyn DukeToday.edu: "Fossil Expert and Primate Conservationist Elwyn Simons Dies at 85"], by Robin A. Smith, 9 March 9 2016.</ref> He was known as the father of modern primate paleontology for his discovery of some of humankind’s earliest antecedents.  <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/17/science/elwyn-l-simons-primate-specialist-who-discovered-early-human-forebears-dies-at-85.html?_r=0 New York Times.com:  "Elwyn L. Simons, Who Discovered Early Human Forebears, Dies at 85"], 16 March 2016, by Margalit Fox . accessed 27 April 2017.</ref>

His [[paleontology]] [[field work]] included sites in [[Egypt]],  [[Madagascar]], and the U.S. state of [[Wyoming]]. {{Sfn|Oakley|2007|p=4}}

==Works==
He authored more than 300&nbsp;scholarly books and research articles, often acting as the sole author or coauthoring with his students and colleagues.{{Sfn|Oakley|2007|p=5}}

During his career, he was an advisor to many doctoral students, including [[Philip D. Gingerich]], [[David Tab Rasmussen|D. Tab Rasmussen]], Erik Seiffert, Richard Kay, David Pilbeam, Ian Tattersall, and Daniel Gebo.{{R|Phylogeny}}  

