{{DISPLAYTITLE:Ice I<sub>c</sub>}}
'''Ice I<sub>c</sub>''' (pronounced "ice one c" or "ice icy") is a [[metastability|metastable]] [[cubic crystal system|cubic]] [[crystalline]] variant of [[ice]]. H. König was the first to identify and deduce the structure of ice I<sub>c</sub>.<ref>{{cite journal|last=König|first=H.|year=1943|title=Eine kubische Eismodifikation|journal=Z. Kristallogr.|volume=105|issue=1|pages=279–286|doi=10.1524/zkri.1943.105.1.279}}</ref> The [[oxygen]] atoms in ice I<sub>c</sub> are arranged in a [[diamond]] structure and is extremely similar to ice I<sub>h</sub> having nearly identical densities and the same lattice constant along the hexagonal puckered-planes.<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Dowell, L. G.; Rinfre, A. P.|year=1960 |title=Low-temperature forms of ice as studied by x-ray diffraction|journal=Nature|volume=189|issue=4757|pages=1144–1148|doi=10.1038/1881144a0|bibcode= 1960Natur.188.1144D}}</ref> It forms at temperatures between 130 and 220 [[kelvin|K]] (−140 and −50&nbsp;°C) upon cooling, and can exist up to 240 K (−33&nbsp;°C) upon warming,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Murray |first=B.J.|author2=Bertram, A. K.|year=2006 |title=Formation and stability of cubic ice in water droplets|journal=Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys. |pmid=16482260 |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=186–192 |doi=10.1039/b513480c|bibcode = 2006PCCP....8..186M |url=https://open.library.ubc.ca/media/download/pdf/52383/1.0041852/3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Murray |first=B.J. |year=2008 |title=The Enhanced formation of cubic ice in aqueous organic acid droplets |pages=025008 |journal=Env. Res. Lett. |volume=3 |doi=10.1088/1748-9326/3/2/025008|bibcode = 2008ERL.....3b5008M |issue=2 }}</ref> when it transforms into [[Ice Ih|ice I<sub>h</sub>]]. 

Apart from forming from supercooled water,<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Mayer, E.; Hallbrucker, A.|year=1987|title=Cubic ice from liquid water|journal=Nature|volume=325|issue=12|pages=601–602|doi=10.1038/325601a0|bibcode= 1987Natur.325..601M}}</ref> ice I<sub>c</sub> has also been reported to form from amorphous ice<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Dowell, L. G.; Rinfre, A. P.|year=1960 |title=Low-temperature forms of ice as studied by x-ray diffraction|journal=Nature|volume=189|issue=4757|pages=1144–1148|doi=10.1038/1881144a0|bibcode= 1960Natur.188.1144D}}</ref> as well as from the high pressure ices [[ice II|II]], [[ice III|III]] and [[ice V|V]].<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Bertie, J. E.; Calvert, L. D., Whalley, E.|year=1963|title=Transformations of Ice II, Ice III, and Ice V at Atmospheric Pressure|journal=J. Chem. Phys.|volume=38|issue=4|pages=840–846|bibcode= 1963JChPh..38..840B|doi = 10.1063/1.1733772 }}</ref> It can form in and is occasionally present in the upper atmosphere<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature03403 |last=Murray |first=B.J.|year=2005 |title=The formation of cubic ice under conditions relevant to Earth's atmosphere |journal=Nature |volume=434 |issue=7030 |pages=202–205 |pmid=15758996|bibcode = 2005Natur.434..202M |display-authors=etal}}, [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v434/n7030/full/nature03403.html]</ref> and is believed to be responsible for the observation of Scheiner's [[Halo (optical phenomenon)|halo]], a rare ring that occurs near 28 degrees from the Sun or the Moon.<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Whalley, E.|year=1981|title=Scheiner's Halo: Evidence for Ice I<sub>c</sub> in the Atmosphere| journal=Science |volume=211 |issue=4480 |pages=389–390 |doi=10.1126/science.211.4480.389|pmid=17748273|bibcode= 1981Sci...211..389W}}</ref>

Ordinary water ice is known as ice I<sub>h</sub> (in the [[Percy Williams Bridgman|Bridgman]] nomenclature). Different types of ice, from [[ice II]] to [[ice XVI]], have been created in the laboratory at different temperatures and pressures.

