[[File:Jan Dembowski.png|thumb|Jan Bohdan Dembowski, before 1936]]

'''Jan Bohdan Dembowski''' (26 December 1889 - 22 September 1963) was a [[Polish people|Polish]] biologist and academic.

Dembowski was born in [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia.  He became the first president of the [[Polish Academy of Sciences]] (1952-1956), [[marshal of the Sejm]] (1952-1957) and [[List of Deputy Chairmen of the Polish Council of State|Deputy Chairman]] of the [[Polish Council of State]] (1952-1957).

In years 1929-1939 he was the editor-in-chief of popular-science journal ''[[Wszechświat]]''.

He was awarded the [[Order of the Builders of Polish People's Republic]] and also received the Commander's Cross with Star of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]]. In 1949 and 1955 state winner of the first degree, a member of the [[Academy of Sciences]] and foreign - [[USSR Academy of Sciences]] (honorary member), the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]], [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] in New York. He died, aged 73, in [[Warsaw]].

