"'''Big Ben'''" was the [[World War II]] [[code name]] for the British project to reconstruct and evaluate captured German missiles such as the [[V-2]] rocket.<ref>{{cite book |last=McGovern |first=James |year=1964 |title=Crossbow and [[Operation Paperclip|Overcast]] |publisher=W. Morrow |location=New York |page=74}}</ref> On 31 July 1944, after the UK agreed to exchange [[Supermarine Spitfires]] for the [[Sweden during World War II#The Bäckebo rocket|wreckage of a V-2 in Sweden]] during World War II, experts at [[Farnborough Airfield|Farnborough]] began an attempt to reconstruct the missile.<ref>{{cite book |last=Collier|first=Basil|title=The Battle of the V-Weapons, 1944-1945 |origyear=1964 |year=1976|publisher=The Emfield Press|location=Yorkshire|language= |isbn=0-7057-0070-4}}</ref>
In late July, 1944, [[Operation Most III]] the [[Armia Krajowa|Polish resistance movement]] (''Armia Krajowa'') succeeded in capturing an intact V2 rocket near the [[Pustków, Podkarpackie Voivodeship|Pustkow]] Testing Centre. It had been launched for a test flight, failed but did not explode and then retrieved still intact from the [[Bug River]], and transferred secretly to London.<ref>[http://www.jewishgen.org/forgottenCamps/Camps/PustEng.html Jewishgen.org: Pustkow Concentration Camp (Poland)] . retrieve 5.15.2013</ref>
