'''''The Atom Besieged: Extraparliamentary Dissent in France and Germany''''' is a 1981 book by Dorothy Nelkin and Michael Pollak.  This book examines the [[Anti-nuclear movement in France|opposition to nuclear power in France]] and [[Anti-nuclear movement in Germany|West Germany]] in the 1970s, which is assessed as being broadly based and widespread. The authors argue that the basic fear which accounted for the vehemence of the opposition is that [[nuclear power]] fundamentally alters the makeup of society.<ref>[http://www.foreignaffairs.org/19810901fabook13132/dorothy-nelkin-michael-pollak/the-atom-besieged-extraparliamentary-dissent-in-france-and-germany.html Reviewed by Andrew J. Pierre, ''Foreign Affairs'', Fall 1981] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040917222056/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/19810901fabook13132/dorothy-nelkin-michael-pollak/the-atom-besieged-extraparliamentary-dissent-in-france-and-germany.html |date=2004-09-17 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/3104828 Book review]</ref>

